author: Super_Shenanigans
body:
IT pro for 20 years here, that has been managing cloud infrastructure in various ways for the last 5 years.  u/borntoperform isn't exactly wrong... but the products we are talking about offer different services.

Palo, Fortinet, and Fireeye provide perimeter security (FireWall), while Crowdstrike, BitDefender, Malware Bytes, and Eset provide endpoint protection (antivirus/antimalware installed directly on the computer or server) 

I have not personally used or researched FireEye, however, I have experience with both Palo and Fortinet - and Palo is by far the leader in the current market.  Their products are made to scale with massive infrastructure services, and trump many other players in the game.  They don't have overwhelming market share because of their cost.

Gartner is a research firm, and while they are not the end all say in things, here is a good example of where technologies lie for the Network Firewall category. (note, linked from Fortinet site because gartner charges for this info directly from their site)

2019 - 

[https://www.fortinet.com/solutions/gartner-network-firewalls](https://www.fortinet.com/solutions/gartner-network-firewalls) 

I'm certain that both companies are winners, as they are both towards the top of their market.

From purely a technology standpoint, I would vote Palo right now, the massive players in the game are more likely to use their products over Fortinet, and with everything that has been going on this year, technology is on top and expanding exponentially - though I can't speculate from a financial standpoint.

author: borntoperform
body:
To be honest, all of the good cybersecurity products are all from privately owned companies. I work in the industry and think Fortinet, Palo Alto, FireEye, and Crowdstrike all provide mediocre products. BitDefender, Malwarebytes, and ESET are good products, but aren't publicly traded.

I would consider ServiceNow, as they are huge in the MSP space, which is a growing sector underneath the cybersecurity umbrella, but that's about it.

author: ReyesA1991
body:
On days like I always go bargain hunting in my watchlist for anything that dropped >5% or FAANGM that drops >2%.

So I'll buy some Square and *maybe* some Sea Limited, Teladoc, Datadog, Apple or Fortinet.

So yes, today is a good day to buy high quality tech stocks. But don't throw all your money in, since Monday could be a down day too. Dollar Cost Average your way in.

I throw $500 into stocks every Friday and have $500 extra in "sideline" cash. If there's any day of the week where the market tanks, I throw in my sideline cash.

If I haven't used my sideline cash by Friday C.O.B. I use it buy dividend stocks like Comcast, Crown Castle, etc.

The trick is to never chase gains or catch a falling knife. But since you can't really time things, you hedge risk by throwing in moderate sums of money over time.

author: MaxandmillionB89
body:
Thanks for your input. I will def check the ETF you mentioned. 
Fortinet has the best SD-WAN in the industry and just recently released the option for multi-cloud. Plus they just acquired Opaq which gives them even more exposure in the cloud area. The only stock that has positive EPS and makes money and has the strongest balance sheet. 
Palo Alto has partnered with all 4 of the largest cloud service providers (AWS, Azure, Alibaba, Google) which makes me believe they know what they are doing. Having these 4 large entries on their side should help them grow even further for many years. 
CrowdStrike like you mentioned is the youngest company for all 3 but disrupting the industry. I don’t know a lot about this company but I keep hearing more and more about it (especially from Jim Cramer). Virgin, Mercedes, Goldman Sachs, Sony, ADP are among their clients which is very impressive considering how long they have been around. 
All 3 companies have its own strengths and weaknesses and room to grow. The question is “who is going to outperform it’s competition?”.

author: MaxandmillionB89
body: Went over the most recent balance sheet for Palo Alto. They do have $1.5MM in long term debts (compared to $0 in LTD for Fortinet) but they also have enough liquidity to pay all of their debts off. That’s strong. Regarding newer companies like CrowdStrike, CloudFlare, Zscaler, Okta... all of them are very promising companies but it’s very difficult for me to justify their current valuations (400-500 forward PE compared to 45 for Palo Alto and Fortinet). I prefer to put my money on an established well run company with a sustainable growth. Palo Alto it is!

author: SteveSharpe
body:
I feel like endpoint security solutions come and go quickly.  A few years ago the hot one was Carbon Black.  Now they are a bad acquisition by VMware.  Crowdstrike will likely end up the same, but I suppose some money could be made if you hold shares when they get acquired.  Hopefully before some other hot new endpoint solution comes along and passes them up.

I think Zscaler is better.  It's true "cloud security" which is what you are looking for.  But I personally would just invest in Palo Alto Networks or Fortinet.  While not traditionally "cloud security", they are buying up all the good cloud solutions and will be the strongest cybersecurity plays for years to come.

author: caseoftx
body:
For those expecting a Microsoft purchase of Tik-Tok US, consider this:

First, Bytedance has been floating the idea of a sale for weeks, meaning they believe it is to their advantage to do so. Most US content platforms are banned in China, including Facebook, Twitter, Github, Google, Youtube, Reddit, Netflix; it is more than reasonable to expect trade reciprocity.

Divesting sounds good, but because of Chinese laws, divesting from China is always inherently a two part process in order to be meaningful: a company has to (1) divest from the Chinese parent company AND (2) divest from the CCP's jurisdictional control. In other words, even Tik Tok is now owned by Microsoft, it would need to move its engineering out of China in order for its platform to be divested from the CCP’s jurisdictional control. Otherwise, it will face similar quandary as Zoom & will  be subject to CCP's intel requests.

Main downside is inconveniencing US Tik Tok users. To be clear, POTUS (regardless of who is Prez) does have exec authority to enact a suspension under the IEEPA-- this is no different than precedent on other sanctions. India did this & the sky didn't fall.

TLDR: Tik Tok sale good for CCP

author: ObservationalHumor
body:
Intel doesn't need a wizard, I'm not sure what it is lately but historically the people running companies need more experience in management within a given industry than they do something like an E.E degree.  Look at who their CTO is if you're looking for technical competence.

AMD isn't doing well because Lisu Su somehow engineered a better processor on her own and by far her personal contributions to really improving the company's fundamentals were in pushing the company into the game console market, amending the wafer supply agreement and putting a much needed axe in the Bulldozer line of processors in favor of a new architecture.  I'm sure she's a great engineer too, but that's not the job she was hired for when she was appointed CEO.  She's made great decisions as a CEO, but this whole idea there's any kind of 'wizard' out there is just wrong.

Intel's problem is their fabs and no 'wizard' is going to fix that.  These are extremely complex and expensive processes that take years to set up and are not easily changed or fixed.  That's a big part of why Intel has basically given up on their 10nm process at this point and is focused on their 7nm node.  If you build something that involved and complex that's fundamentally flawed you can't just turn it around and make it work.  Intel's literally been trying for years here and that more than anything else is what's contributed to AMD's meteoric rise.
